{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:24:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:24:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.06,0.05,0.6,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1056"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"6090"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of progressive weakness and numbness in her right hand. She works as a metalworker and frequently uses vibrating tools. She has noticed difficulty extending her wrist and fingers, particularly when trying to grip objects. She denies any trauma or injury. She has a history of right carpal tunnel syndrome two years ago which resolved with physiotherapy. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is weakness of wrist and finger extension (2/5), with preserved flexion. There is reduced sensation over the anatomical snuffbox and the dorsal aspect of the first web space. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to provide the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the right wrist","Computed tomography of the right elbow","X-ray of the right humerus","Nerve conduction studies","Magnetic resonance imaging of the right wrist"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of radial nerve palsy, including wrist drop (weakness of wrist and finger extension) and sensory loss in the radial nerve distribution. The occupational history suggests possible compression neuropathy from prolonged pressure or vibration exposure. Her previous history of carpal tunnel syndrome indicates susceptibility to compression neuropathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E are the most appropriate next step as they can confirm the diagnosis, localise the site of compression, and determine the severity of nerve injury. This information is crucial for treatment planning and prognosis. They can also help differentiate this new problem from a recurrence of her previous carpal tunnel syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of the right wrist\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there were symptoms suggesting a space-occupying lesion or if nerve conduction studies were inconclusive. While this patient has had previous carpal tunnel syndrome, her current symptoms are not consistent with median nerve compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the right humerus\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was a history of trauma or suspicion of fracture. In this case, there is no history of injury to suggest the need for plain radiographs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the right wrist\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in diagnosing radial nerve compression, which typically occurs more proximally in the arm. While ultrasound can be useful for carpal tunnel syndrome, the distribution of symptoms and signs does not fit with median nerve compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography of the right elbow\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the initial investigation of choice for a suspected nerve compression syndrome. CT is more useful for evaluating bony abnormalities rather than soft tissue or nerve pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pattern of weakness and sensory loss clearly points to radial nerve involvement. While the history and examination findings are sufficient to make a clinical diagnosis, nerve conduction studies are necessary to confirm the diagnosis, determine the exact site of compression, and guide management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radial nerve injury commonly presents with wrist drop and reduced finger extension, with sensory loss over the anatomical snuffbox.","Physical examination is the key first step in diagnosing peripheral nerve injuries, before proceeding to electrodiagnostic studies.","Occupational history is crucial in identifying compression neuropathies, as certain positions and repetitive movements can lead to nerve injury."],"references":["Silver S, Ledford CC, Vogel KJ, Arnold JJ. Peripheral Nerve Entrapment and Injury in the Upper Extremity. Am Fam Physician. 2021;103(5):275-285. Available online at ; https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2021/0301/p275.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T22:03:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-21T22:03:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7358"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86458"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing 